The are two different T shapes, they can be differeciated fro the size of the top of the T(the line that is perdindicular and extends on two sides).  The back is the T shape with the smaller of the two tops, while the seat has the larger of the top.

description.text:
Allows you to go directly from a 4 inch blast gate in your dust collection system to a 3 inch hose in one step.
I've added a small groove around the 3 inch end to help hold the flex hose in place under a hose clamp. No more hose slipping off.
I've made two variations to allow for different sizes of hoses:
YadapClapet4poEx_par_3po-1.stl has a diametre of slightly less than 3".
YadapClapet4poEx 3po1a.stl has a diametre of slightly more than 3". I find this size fits perfectly with the grey flex hose I have.
To strengthen the part for use in a workshop environment, I used ABS and then applied acetone with a brush. If using PLA make sure the layers are bonding well as it is being formed.

description.text: This is a selector that I made for my automatic transmission (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1094616). It has an interlock mechanism and manual mode, so works like a real one. I made this model because I plan to print my automatic transmission and put solenoids controlled by Arduino, so I needed a way to select between modes, and even select each gear manually. Why? Well, I have an engine model that runs like a real one and I want to put the automatic transmission and all that to simulate a car running on the road. I already have a working sketch (program) for Arduino to control the solenoids on the automatic transmission, and I have the engine model working, so now all I need is a 3D printer to print all the transmission, selector, differential, etc. The wheels are going to be connected to a big flywheel to simulate the momentum of a moving car. This project is not for everybody, but I wanted to share it anyway. You are going to need 3mm rods, some springs and a 5mm steel ball (example: from a ball bearing). There are holders to put a cover strip for the Y axis, but since is so thing would not be practical to print that part, so you most make it yourself from maybe paperboard or whatever you want. You can make the cover strip for the X axis too. If you have any question, let me know.

For this project I had to make a 3D object out of acrylic using the epilog engraver.  This ring is made of six seperate parts: four fork-shaped ring parts, one long ring part and an 'm' that snaps into the ring once it is glued together.  The 'm' should be printed seperately from the other ring parts if you want it to be a different color.  I chose blue for the 'm' and clear for the actual ring.  The dimensioning for this project was a little more complicated than the others but its worth it in the end because it's by far the best thing I've made yet!

To make the SuperHero Ring you should make the ring parts and 'm' in Inventor since that program allows for easier dimensioning.  For printing,you should use 3mm acrylic and vector cut it at a speed of 12, a power of 100 and a frequency of 5000.  Once all six parts are cut out, glue the five ring parts together with the 'm' on top as it will be on the finished ring.  Use a clamp to hold all of the pieces together and use minimal glue - it goes a long way and you dont want it to get all over the acrylic because it won't look as nice.

A necessary accessory for the old-school electrical engineer/socially-incompetent EE student in your life, this is obviously a belt holster for a TI-68 calculator. It's designed to be used with the cover ON and CLOSED. In this configuration fitment is great: the 68's slight taper allows for smooth placement and the calculator is secure once inside. Tolerances were picked with the rubber feet on the back of the 68's case in mind, so if you've lost yours to decades of undeserved mistreatment things might be a bit loose. Insertion with the case on but open is also possible, and gives a very snug fit. If you plan on running with your calculator in your belt holster (why?) that'd be the way to go.

This is an earlier, printable version of the new MakerBot MK7 filament drive block. During the development of the MK7, I was hoping we could make the filament drive portion of the design printable. It worked really well for testing and prototyping, but it was not feasible for us to scale it for production. Instead, we converted it to injection molding and that is how you have the MK7 we offer today. This filament drive block is a nice, single piece and prints really well on an MK6. It will print even better on an MK7. It has dual filament inlet channels, and you can probably mod it to do all sorts of cool things. I've provided the original solidworks and an STL output for your ease of use. A couple things I'm proud of:

  • The 'mouse ears' on the corners help it stick better and remain flat, yet are easy to peel off.

  • The tiny hole slots which cause the holes to be printed as part of the outer shell. The slot is too small to show up in the final part, and you get a really nice looking bolt hole.
Print and use as you would the normal filament drive block.

A little flower-shaped sconce sized for a birthday candle. Integrate it into a design, or print some and glue them onto something else, to make a secure place to stick little candles.  
I made this because the birthday girl wanted an apple crisp instead of a cake, and it's not so easy to get candles to stay upright in apple crisp.  
The object they're sitting on in the photos is a three-dimensional ambigram of the guest of honor's name and age, which doesn't seem like it would be of general interest - but it was well-liked and a great illustration of what 3D printing can do and how it excels at one-off designs.

The default settings and STL file provided, printed on my Cube printer, fit the candles I had available, with some forcing - which I liked because it holds them nice and tight. A looser fit might be better, though.  
Sorry the Customizer shows it so small - if anyone knows how to fix it, let me know!

This is part 1 of a 2-part system for storing 1/4 sockets for your socket wrenches. It prints a 4x2 array of holders customized to each of your sockets. These slide into a base (see: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1215154). It's probably overkill for most people, but the sockets push onto a post (slightly tapered) and fit in a custom-sized hole (I measured my socket set with a caliper---you can adjust the diameters in the code). Customizer lets choose up to 8 of these to print at a time. Each will have the size written on all 4 sides. I print one color for metric and another for US.

Notes: Easy prints

Larger-Sized Sockets Maximum size is 1/2 for US and 13mm for metric. If you would like to make a set to handle larger ones, it is fairly easy, but you need to make changes to both projects (the one that prints the holder and the one that prints the individual sockets). The variable to change in both codes is BASE. Currently, it is set at 21mm. It represents the length of the sides of the main cube of the individual socket holders. Because the text takes up 1mm on each side and needs about 1mm behind it for support, BASE needs to be set at about 4mm more than the diameter of the largest socket you want to be able to put into this. I did caliper measurements of the next two sizes up for both metric and US, just uncomment the relevant sections of the code. Obviously you can go even larger by making your own caliper measurements, but in general this design is probably best suited for the smaller sockets and not so much for the larger ones.

OK, Putting up the Christmas Tree can be a pain in the phalanges.  This little widget is sort of a Christmas tree stand drill bit.  Just attach it to a drill as you would a bit or screw driver attachment, then place it on the bent post that tightens the tree into the stand.  It works pretty slick to tighten the tree and get it where you want it.  I leveled it myself and had my wife standing by to tell me if I had it level.
Luckily for me, I only put one Christmas tree up every year.  My stand has 5mm threaded rods.  For those of you who are richer \ Insaner than me, and put up more than one tree or a have huge freakin' tree, feel free to hack this up and make it fit whatever you have in your living room\ ball room \gazebo\ guest house\ padded room.
